The EDDA detector. It consists of scintillator
bars and rings designed to measure the points, at which
the scattered proton and its recoil partner traverse
the hodoscope.  The kinematic relationship between
these angles are used to identify elastic scattering
events. Additional details see in original paper.

this encompasses the purely statistical error from the

P-carbon scattering and errors introduced by angle-
reconstruction and cuts applied in the data analysis.
.The systematic errors which will be functions
smoothly varying with beam momentum and scattering
angle. This comprises the uncertainty on the overall
detection efficiency for pp elastic scattering and the
uncertainty on possible contaminations from pp-
inelastic  reactions.
.The total error is the quadratic sum of ERR-S
and ERR-1.
All data do not contain two types of normalization
uncertainties:  an overall normalization error of the
whole data set of less 1.5% due to the absolute
normalization at beam momentum 1455 MeV/c. There is an
Additional systematic uncertainty due to the relative
normalization of 2.5% common to all data points at the
same energy. This error does not apply at the
normalization point at 1455 MeV/c. The relative
normalization uncertainties at different beam momenta
are uncorrelated. This is a conservative upper limit
especially for beam momenta close to 1455 MeV/c.
